This is the issue! In the Text state, when an end tag is encountered, it simply pops the current node and transitions back to the original state. However, the problem with the test case `<body><p><textarea>one<p>two` is that for textarea, the parser should be looking specifically for a `</textarea>` end tag, not just stopping at any `<p>` tag.

Looking back at the TokeniserState, I see that for RCData elements like textarea, when a `<` is encountered, it goes to `RcdataLessthanSign`, which then looks for the appropriate end tag (in this case, `</textarea>`). 

The issue may be in the `RcdataLessthanSign` state. Let me look at it again:

Looking at the `RcdataLessthanSign` state in TokeniserState.java:
```java
RcdataLessthanSign {
    // from < in rcdata
    void read(Tokeniser t, CharacterReader r) {
        if (r.matches('/')) {
            t.createTempBuffer();
            t.advanceTransition(RCDATAEndTagOpen);
            // diverge from spec: got a start tag, but there's no appropriate end tag (</title>), so rather than
            // consuming to EOF; break out here
        } else {
            t.emit("<");
            t.transition(Rcdata);
        }
    }
}
```

The issue is in the comment! When an inappropriate end tag is encountered (like `<p>` when inside a `<textarea>`), it should NOT break out and treat it as regular data content. The comment suggests this is a deviation from spec, but it's causing the problem.

Let me understand the difference better by running a test to see what's actually happening:

