    if (charBuffer.length() > 0) {
        String str = charBuffer.toString();
        charBuffer.delete(0, charBuffer.length());
        return new Token.Character(str);
    } else {
        isEmitPending = false;
        return emitPending;
    }
}
```

The issue is that when I call `emitTagPending()` in the middle of the `state.read()` call, it sets `emitPending` and `isEmitPending` to true. Then the while loop `while (!isEmitPending)` in the `read()` method will exit, and the method returns the pending token (the `</textarea>` end tag).

So the end tag token is returned to the TreeBuilder, which processes it and pops the textarea element. Then the TreeBuilder calls `tokeniser.read()` again. The tokenizer is now in the Data state (due to my transition) and processing continues from the unconsumed `<`.

This flow should be correct. The infinite loop might occur if there's another issue. Let me try running the test without the debug class:

